name: Dyana Gayle
comments: Singer, pianist and restaurant owner. She got her start in show business by making transcriptions in Hollywood film studios and as a singer on local Southern California radio stations. By early 1942, shortly after the U.S. entered World War II and defense factories were operating on a 24-hour basis, radio stations also were on 24-hours a day to provide entertainment for these workers. Dyana Gayle had a program heard late at night and she became known as "The Sweetheart of the Swing Shift." In 1943 she started her first nation-wide radio series, "Your Home Front Reporter," heard over the Columbia Broadcasting System. She was with CBS for most of the 1940s. She also recorded for the armed forces radio service and made voice dubbings for several different movie actresses.  By the end of that decade she began performing in night clubs and restaurants in California, Nevada, Arizona and other western states. She also operated the Nite Cap and Nicole's French restaurant in Hollywood.

He played the part of Dr. Otto Siedler in the first performance of the 1930 success operetta Im weißen Rößl in Berlin. When the Nazis came to power in 1933 he left Germany and moved to Austria where he continued to work in film. He later moved to France and then on to the Netherlands. He was arrested there, held for a while at Westerbork transit camp and later moved to Auschwitz where he was killed.
